However, you can simulate hybrid inheritance in Java using hierarchical and multi-level inheritance with the help of a single base class.

Example: Hybrid Inheritance Without Interfaces or Multiple Inheritance
// Parent class (Base class)
class A {
    void methodA() {
        System.out.println("Method from Class A");
    }
}

// Intermediate class inheriting from A (Multi-level inheritance)
class B extends A {
    void methodB() {
        System.out.println("Method from Class B");
    }
}

// Another subclass inheriting from A (Hierarchical inheritance)
class C extends A {
    void methodC() {
        System.out.println("Method from Class C");
    }
}

// Subclass inheriting indirectly from both A and B
class D extends B {
    void methodD() {
        System.out.println("Method from Class D");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        D obj = new D();
        obj.methodA(); // Inherited from A
        obj.methodB(); // Inherited from B
        obj.methodD(); // D's own method

        C objC = new C();
        objC.methodA(); // Inherited from A
        objC.methodC(); // C's own method
    }
}

